7. Around the clock.  If something is done ‘around the clock’, then it is done all day and all night without stopping.

30
00:05:04,644 --> 00:05:13,151
“Oh yes. We have around the clock security. Noboby's getting into this place.”

31
00:05:13,151 --> 00:05:22,833
8. To call it a day.  This means to decide to stop doing something, either permanently or for a while depending on the context.

32
00:05:22,833 --> 00:05:28,799
“I’m too tired to finish my homework so I’m going to call it a day and finish it tomorrow.”

33
00:05:28,799 --> 00:05:40,064
9. In the blink of an eye.  If something happens ‘in the blink of an eye’ then it happens very quickly, just like a blink.

34
00:05:40,765 --> 00:05:45,735
“A calculator can solve the maths problem in the blink of an eye.”

35
00:05:45,735 --> 00:06:01,786
10. To kill time . This phrase is used informally and it means to spend time doing something unimportant, particularly when waiting for something.

36
00:06:01,786 --> 00:06:07,464
“Yes, we’ll go shopping at the airport to kill time before the flight.”

37
00:06:07,464 --> 00:06:17,919
11. Like clockwork . If something happens ‘like clockwork’, then it happens very smoothly and easily.

38
00:06:17,919 --> 00:06:24,247
“The presentation ran like clockwork. Everyone was very happy.”

39
00:06:24,247 --> 00:06:39,148
12. On the dot . This is an informal phrase which means exactly on time. “She starts work at 9am on the dot. Not 9.03am.”

40
00:06:39,148 --> 00:06:48,416
13. To do time (to serve time).  This is a colloquial term meaning to be in prison.

41
00:06:48,416 --> 00:06:53,029
“He’s doing time for money laundering.”

42
00:06:53,029 --> 00:07:03,299
14. To turn back time . To ‘turn back time’ means to recreate, remember, or imagine things as they were before.

43
00:07:03,299 --> 00:07:12,565
“I like to reminisce while looking through old photographs, but I do wish I could just turn back time.”

44
00:07:12,565 --> 00:07:21,483
15. To have a whale of a time . This means to have a brilliant time, to really enjoy oneself.

45
00:07:21,483 --> 00:07:27,900
“I had a whale of a time learning to ski, until I broke my leg.”

46
00:07:27,900 --> 00:07:41,531
16. To lose track of the time . To ‘lose track of the time’ means to be unaware of how much time has passed, or to not be sure of what the time is.

47
00:07:41,531 --> 00:07:48,358
“I’m so sorry I’m late. I lost track of the time!”

48
00:07:48,358 --> 00:07:56,782
17. Free time.  ‘Free time’ refers to time available for hobbies and activities you enjoy.

49
00:07:56,782 --> 00:08:01,820
“In my free time, I like to play football. What do you like to do?"

50
00:08:02,341 --> 00:08:13,756
18. Spur of the moment . Something done in the ‘spur of the moment’ is done impulsively, without planning in advance.

51
00:08:13,756 --> 00:08:23,903
“We aren’t going to Argentina now, instead we’re going to Switzerland! Don’t ask me why, it was a spur of the moment decision.”

52
00:08:23,903 --> 00:08:40,510
19. Behind the times . If something is ‘behind the times’, it is not using the latest technology, ideas or techniques. It could also be referred to as ‘out of date’.

53
00:08:40,510 --> 00:08:46,780
“This library is so behind the times. They don’t even have a computer!”

54
00:08:46,780 --> 00:08:55,637
20. To hit the big time . This is an idiomatic phrase which means to become very successful or famous.

55
00:08:55,637 --> 00:09:03,265
“She hit the big time and got a part in a very successful film after years of hard work.”

56
00:09:03,265 --> 00:09:10,830
21. Hour of need.  An ‘hour of need’ is a time when most help is needed.

57
00:09:10,830 --> 00:09:14,333
“Thank you so much for helping us in our hour of need.”

58
00:09:14,333 --> 00:09:22,518
22. A laugh a minute.  You could use this phrase to describe someone who is very funny.

59
00:09:22,518 --> 00:09:29,048
“John’s great. He’s a laugh a minute, so funny.”

60
00:09:29,048 --> 00:09:41,138
23. Like there’s no tomorrow . To do something ‘like there’s no tomorrow’ means to do it in a quick or careless way without considering the future.

61
00:09:41,138 --> 00:09:46,426
“He’s spending money like there’s no tomorrow!”

62
00:09:46,426 --> 00:09:57,559
24. Long time no see . This is informally used as a greeting to mean ‘it’s a long time since we last met’.

63
00:09:57,559 --> 00:10:01,739
“Christopher, long time no see!”

64
00:10:01,739 --> 00:10:10,473
25. A mile a minute.  If something is happening ‘a mile a minute’, it is happening at a very fast rate.

65
00:10:10,473 --> 00:10:15,097
“I can barely understand Connor because he talks a mile a minute.”

66
00:10:15,097 --> 00:10:24,373
26. Now and then If something happens ‘now and then’, it happens occasionally.

67
00:10:24,373 --> 00:10:27,754
“I don’t see her much but we go for coffee now and then.”

68
00:10:27,754 --> 00:10:43,251
27. The moment of truth.  A time when a person or thing is tested, a decision has to be made, or a crisis has to be faced might be referred to as ‘the moment of truth’.

69
00:10:43,251 --> 00:10:52,723
“Grace has spent hours baking the perfect cake, but now it is the moment of truth: time to taste it.”

70
00:10:52,723 --> 00:11:09,775
28. To have too much time on one’s hands.  To have ‘too much time on your hands’ means to have lots of extra time. We often use this phrase to describe someone who is engaged in unhelpful or useless activities.

71
00:11:09,775 --> 00:11:14,439
“She’s such a gossip. She obviously has far too much time on her hands.”

72
00:11:14,439 --> 00:11:21,689
29. Once in a blue moon
	This means it rarely happens.

73
00:11:21,689 --> 00:11:30,669
“I don’t speak to my old uni mates these days. I mean Fernando will call me for a catch-up once in a blue moon, but apart from that we have all lost touch.”

74
00:11:30,669 --> 00:11:39,708
30. Donkey’s years .  ‘Donkey’s years’ is an informal way of saying a long time.

75
00:11:39,708 --> 00:11:44,261
“Adam and I have been friends for donkey’s years!”

